### 🇦🇪 United Arab Emirates — Ambition-Led, Institutionally Driven

**Who it applies to:** All entities operating in the UAE. Those within free zones — particularly the DIFC and ADGM — face the most specifically defined current obligations.

**Where things stand:** The UAE has no comprehensive AI statute, but it is one of the most institutionally active AI governance environments in the world. In **January 2026**, the UAE became the first country globally to integrate AI as an advisory participant in its Cabinet, its Ministerial Development Council, and the boards of all federal entities and state-owned enterprises. This is not symbolic — it formalises the pace at which the regulatory environment is expected to mature.

The **UAE AI Charter** (June 2024) establishes 12 ethical principles governing the responsible development and use of AI, covering algorithmic bias, data privacy, transparency, human oversight, and accountability. While non-binding, the Charter functions as the operative governance standard against which conduct is assessed. Within the DIFC, amendments to the data protection framework impose specific obligations on AI systems that interact with personal data, and a dedicated AI Licence has been introduced for entities operating AI-specific businesses within the zone. Beyond regulation, the **Stargate UAE** project — a 5-gigawatt AI data centre campus in Abu Dhabi, backed by the government's technology investment arm MGX — signals the infrastructure scale that formal regulatory architecture will need to match.

> **Watch point:** DIFC and ADGM-registered entities have live data protection and AI disclosure obligations now. Mainland operators face ethical charter expectations and evolving sector guidance. The regulatory architecture is being built in step with the infrastructure — organisations that establish governance frameworks now will be considerably better positioned when binding requirements follow.

